---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import SidebarTOC from '../components/SidebarTOC.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const levelNumber = 1;
const levelTitle = 'SEO & GEO Basics';
const levelSubtitle = 'The 5 Essential HTML Tools for Making Websites Search-Friendly';

const sections = [
  { id: 'what-is-seo-geo', title: 'What is SEO & GEO?', icon: '🔍' },
  { id: 'library-analogy', title: 'The Library Analogy', icon: '📚' },
  { id: 'five-tools', title: 'The 5 Essential Tools', icon: '🛠️' },
  { id: 'tool-title', title: 'Tool #1: The ID Card (title)', icon: '🏷️' },
  { id: 'tool-h1', title: 'Tool #2: The Boss (h1)', icon: '📌' },
  { id: 'tool-links', title: 'Tool #3: The Doors (Links)', icon: '🔗' },
  { id: 'tool-alt', title: 'Tool #4: The Eyes (Alt Text)', icon: '🖼️' },
  { id: 'tool-schema', title: 'Tool #5: The Form (Schema)', icon: '📊' },
  { id: 'search-intent', title: 'Search Intent: The "Why"', icon: '🧠' },
  { id: 'view-source', title: 'How to View Source Code', icon: '🔍' },
  { id: 'checklist', title: 'Practice Checklist', icon: '✅' },
  { id: 'why-coders', title: 'Why Companies Hire Coders', icon: '💼' },
  { id: 'off-page-seo', title: 'Beyond Your Page: Off-Page SEO', icon: '🌐' },
  { id: 'quiz', title: 'Level 1 Quiz', icon: '🎯' }
];
---

<Layout title={`Level ${levelNumber}: ${levelTitle} | Waseem's SEO Guide`}>
  <!-- Breadcrumbs -->
  <nav class="breadcrumbs" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
    <ol>
      <li><a href={`${base}/`}>Home</a></li>
      <li aria-current="page">Level {levelNumber}: {levelTitle}</li>
    </ol>
  </nav>

  <header>
    <span class="badge">LEVEL {levelNumber}</span>
    <h1>📘 {levelTitle}</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">{levelSubtitle}</p>
    <div class="reading-time-badge">⏱️ ~35 min read</div>
    <div class="meta">
      <strong>Created for:</strong> Waseem (English Teacher & Coder)<br />
      <strong>Level:</strong> Beginner - No prior SEO knowledge needed<br />
      <strong>Time:</strong> ~35 minutes to read + 10-question quiz<br />
      <strong>Date:</strong> February 2026<br />
      <strong>Format:</strong> Learn → Practice → Quiz
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- Table of Contents -->
  <SidebarTOC sections={sections} />

  <!-- What is SEO & GEO -->
  <section id="what-is-seo-geo">
    <h2>1. What is SEO & GEO?</h2>

    <h3>🔍 SEO (Search Engine Optimization)</h3>
    <p>Making your website <strong>easy to find</strong> on Google.</p>
    <div class="tip-box">
      <h4>💡 Analogy</h4>
      <p>Like putting the right label on a book so the librarian knows where to shelve it.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>🤖 GEO (Generative Engine Optimization)</h3>
    <p>Making your website <strong>easy for AI to understand and quote</strong>.</p>
    <div class="tip-box">
      <h4>💡 Analogy</h4>
      <p>Like writing clearly so an AI can read your book and share your information.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <h4>🔧 Why Coders Matter</h4>
      <p>Marketers can write content, but <strong>only coders can fix the code</strong>. You build the foundation; they decorate the house.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Library Analogy -->
  <section id="library-analogy">
    <h2>2. 📚 The Library Analogy</h2>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Real World</th>
          <th>Internet World</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>📚 Library</td>
          <td>🌐 Google</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>📖 Book</td>
          <td>🌐 Website</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>📋 Book Label</td>
          <td>🏷️ SEO Tags</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>📇 Card Catalog</td>
          <td>📝 Schema</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>🚪 Door</td>
          <td>🔗 Link</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="warning-box">
      <h4>⚠️ Key Insight</h4>
      <p>If Google can't find your "book," it doesn't matter how good it is!</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The 5 Essential Tools -->
  <section id="five-tools">
    <h2>3. 🛠️ The 5 Essential Tools</h2>

    <p>As a coder, you need to master these <strong>5 HTML tools</strong>:</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>#</th>
          <th>Tool</th>
          <th>Code</th>
          <th>Purpose</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>1</td>
          <td><strong>ID Card</strong></td>
          <td><code>&lt;title&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Tells Google your page name</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>2</td>
          <td><strong>Boss</strong></td>
          <td><code>&lt;h1&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Tells Google your main topic</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>3</td>
          <td><strong>Doors</strong></td>
          <td><code>&lt;a href=""&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Helps Google navigate</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>4</td>
          <td><strong>Eyes</strong></td>
          <td><code>alt=""</code></td>
          <td>Helps Google "see" images</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>5</td>
          <td><strong>Form</strong></td>
          <td><code>Schema (JSON)</code></td>
          <td>Helps AI trust your facts</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <!-- Tool #1: Title Tag -->
  <section id="tool-title">
    <h2>4. 🏷️ Tool #1: The ID Card (&lt;title&gt;)</h2>

    <h3>What It Is</h3>
    <p>The hidden title that Google reads first. It appears in:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Search results</li>
      <li>Browser tabs</li>
      <li>Bookmarks</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Where It Lives</h3>
    <p>Inside the <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> section (humans don't see it, but bots do).</p>

    <h3>Example</h3>
    <pre><code>&lt;html&gt;
  &lt;head&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;English Lessons for Beginners | Waseem's School&lt;/title&gt;
  &lt;/head&gt;
  &lt;body&gt;
    &lt;!-- Visible content here --&gt;
  &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;</code></pre>

    <h3>What Google Learns</h3>
    <p><em>"This page is about <strong>English Lessons</strong>, for <strong>Beginners</strong>, at <strong>Waseem's School</strong>."</em></p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <h4>✅ Best Practices</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Keep it under 60 characters</li>
        <li>Include your main keyword</li>
        <li>Add your brand name</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Tool #2: H1 Heading -->
  <section id="tool-h1">
    <h2>5. 📌 Tool #2: The Boss (&lt;h1&gt;)</h2>

    <h3>What It Is</h3>
    <p>The main heading that humans see on the page. Only <strong>ONE</strong> per page!</p>

    <h3>Hierarchy</h3>
    <pre><code>&lt;h1&gt; = Main Title (The Boss)
&lt;h2&gt; = Chapter Title
&lt;h3&gt; = Subsection
&lt;p&gt;  = Regular text</code></pre>

    <h3>Example</h3>
    <pre><code>&lt;h1&gt;Free English Lessons for Beginners&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Grammar Basics&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Present Tense&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Learn how to use present tense...&lt;/p&gt;</code></pre>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <h4>✅ Best Practices</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Only ONE <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> per page</li>
        <li>Make it descriptive</li>
        <li>Include your main keyword</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Tool #3: Links -->
  <section id="tool-links">
    <h2>6. 🔗 Tool #3: The Doors (&lt;a&gt; Links)</h2>

    <h3>What It Is</h3>
    <p>Links that help Google (and users) navigate from one page to another.</p>

    <h3>Example</h3>
    <pre><code>&lt;a href="contact.html"&gt;Contact Us&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a href="https://example.com"&gt;Visit Example&lt;/a&gt;</code></pre>

    <div class="warning-box">
      <h4>⚠️ Why It Matters</h4>
      <p>If a page has <strong>no links</strong> pointing to it, Google <strong>cannot find it</strong>. Links are like <strong>roads</strong> between pages.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <h4>✅ Best Practices</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Use descriptive link text (not "click here")</li>
        <li>Make sure all links work (no broken doors!)</li>
        <li>Link to important pages from your homepage</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Tool #4: Alt Attributes -->
  <section id="tool-alt">
    <h2>7. 🖼️ Tool #4: The Eyes (alt= Text)</h2>

    <h3>What It Is</h3>
    <p>A description of an image for Google (which is "blind" to pictures).</p>

    <h3>Example</h3>
    <pre><code>&lt;img src="cake.jpg" alt="Chocolate cake with strawberries on top"&gt;</code></pre>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <h4>🔧 Why It Matters</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Google <strong>cannot see images</strong>, only read text</li>
        <li><code>alt</code> text tells Google what the image shows</li>
        <li>Helps with accessibility (screen readers)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Bad vs Good</h3>
    <pre><code>&lt;!-- ❌ Bad --&gt;
&lt;img src="img123.jpg" alt="image"&gt;

&lt;!-- ✅ Good --&gt;
&lt;img src="cake.jpg" alt="Chocolate cake recipe"&gt;</code></pre>
  </section>

  <!-- Tool #5: Schema Markup -->
  <section id="tool-schema">
    <h2>8. 📊 Tool #5: The Form (Schema)</h2>

    <h3>What It Is</h3>
    <p>Structured data (JSON) that tells AI <strong>exact facts</strong> about your content.</p>

    <h3>Analogy</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Without Schema:</strong> Writing an essay to the bank</li>
      <li><strong>With Schema:</strong> Filling out a clear form</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Example: Local Business</h3>
    <pre><code>&lt;script type="application/ld+json"&gt;
&#123;
  "@type": "LocalBusiness",
  "name": "Waseem English School",
  "address": &#123;
    "@type": "PostalAddress",
    "streetAddress": "123 Main St",
    "addressLocality": "Haifa",
    "addressCountry": "Israel"
  &#125;,
  "telephone": "+972-53-426-0632",
  "priceRange": "$"
&#125;
&lt;/script&gt;</code></pre>

    <h3>Common Types</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><code>LocalBusiness</code> - For shops, schools, offices</li>
      <li><code>Recipe</code> - For cooking recipes</li>
      <li><code>Product</code> - For e-commerce</li>
      <li><code>Article</code> - For blog posts</li>
      <li><code>Event</code> - For concerts, workshops</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <h4>✅ Best Practices</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Put it in the <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> section</li>
        <li>Use correct JSON format</li>
        <li>Test with Google's <a href="https://search.google.com/test/rich-results" target="_blank">Rich Results Test</a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Search Intent -->
  <section id="search-intent">
    <h2>9. 🧠 Search Intent: The "Why" Behind the Query</h2>

    <h3>🧠 What Is Search Intent?</h3>
    <p>Think of search intent as the <strong>motivation</strong> behind someone's search. When a person types words into Google, they have a goal in mind.</p>

    <p>For example, if someone searches <strong>"best running shoes"</strong>, they might want to:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Buy</strong> shoes right now (transactional intent)</li>
      <li><strong>Compare</strong> different brands (commercial intent)</li>
      <li><strong>Learn</strong> how to choose running shoes (informational intent)</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Modern AI engines don't just match <strong>words</strong>—they try to understand <strong>intent</strong>. Your content needs to match what the user actually wants.</p>

    <div class="reflect-box">
      <h4>🤔 Reflection #1</h4>
      <p>If someone searches "how to fix a leaky faucet," are they looking to buy, to learn, or to find a service? How would you write the H1 heading to match that intent?</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reflect-box">
      <h4>🤔 Reflection #2</h4>
      <p>Look at your own project's main keyword. What is the user <em>really</em> trying to achieve? Does your content deliver that?</p>
    </div>

    <h3>💻 Code Example: Intent-Aligned Headings</h3>
    <p>Notice how the heading structure changes based on what the user wants:</p>

    <pre><code>&lt;!-- ❓ Informational Intent (User wants to LEARN) --&gt;
&lt;h1&gt;How to Fix a Leaky Faucet in 5 Simple Steps&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Tools You'll Need&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Step-by-Step Instructions&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;When to Call a Professional&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;!-- 🛒 Transactional Intent (User wants to BUY) --&gt;
&lt;h1&gt;Buy Premium Faucets | Free Shipping & Installation&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Featured Products&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Customer Reviews&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Add to Cart&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;!-- 🔧 Service Intent (User wants to HIRE) --&gt;
&lt;h1&gt;Emergency Faucet Repair | Licensed Plumbers&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Our Services&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Why Choose Us&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Request a Quote&lt;/h2&gt;</code></pre>

    <h3>Types of Search Intent</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Intent Type</th>
          <th>User Goal</th>
          <th>Example Query</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>📚 Informational</td>
          <td>To learn</td>
          <td>"how to tie a tie"</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>🛍️ Transactional</td>
          <td>To buy</td>
          <td>"buy nike shoes online"</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>🔍 Navigational</td>
          <td>To find a specific site</td>
          <td>"facebook login"</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>🏢 Commercial</td>
          <td>To compare/research</td>
          <td>"best laptop 2026"</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="key-takeaway-box">
      <h4>🎯 Key Takeaway</h4>
      <p>Match your content to the user's goal, not just their keywords. AI engines prioritize pages that satisfy the <em>intent</em> behind the search.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- View Source Code -->
  <section id="view-source">
    <h2>10. 🔍 How to View Source Code</h2>

    <h3>Step-by-Step</h3>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Open any website</strong> (e.g., <code>example.com</code>)</li>
      <li><strong>Right-click</strong> anywhere on the page</li>
      <li><strong>Select "View Page Source"</strong> (or press <code>Ctrl+U</code> on Windows / <code>Cmd+Option+U</code> on Mac)</li>
      <li><strong>Use Search</strong> to find what you need:
        <ul>
          <li>Press <code>Ctrl+F</code> (Windows) or <code>Cmd+F</code> (Mac)</li>
          <li>Type what you're looking for:
            <ul>
              <li><code>&lt;title</code> → Find the page title</li>
              <li><code>&lt;h1</code> → Find the main heading</li>
              <li><code>alt=</code> → Find image descriptions</li>
              <li><code>ld+json</code> → Find Schema</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <h4>💡 Pro Tip</h4>
      <p>Don't try to read everything! Just <strong>search</strong> for what you need.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Practice Checklist -->
  <section id="checklist">
    <h2>11. ✅ Practice Checklist</h2>

    <h3>Weekly Practice (5 minutes)</h3>
    <div class="checklist">
      <label><input type="checkbox" /> Open 3 different websites</label>
      <label><input type="checkbox" /> View Source (<code>Ctrl+U</code>)</label>
      <label><input type="checkbox" /> Find the <code>&lt;title&gt;</code> tag</label>
      <label><input type="checkbox" /> Find the <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> tag</label>
      <label><input type="checkbox" /> Find one <code>alt=</code> attribute</label>
      <label><input type="checkbox" /> Ask: "Is this clear and descriptive?"</label>
    </div>

    <h3>Your Own Website Checklist</h3>
    <p>Before launching any page, check:</p>
    <div class="checklist">
      <label><input type="checkbox" /> Does it have a <code>&lt;title&gt;</code> with keywords?</label>
      <label><input type="checkbox" /> Does it have ONE <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code>?</label>
      <label><input type="checkbox" /> Are all images tagged with <code>alt=</code>?</label>
      <label><input type="checkbox" /> Do all links work?</label>
      <label><input type="checkbox" /> Is Schema added (if applicable)?</label>
      <label><input type="checkbox" /> Does the content match user search intent?</label>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Why Companies Hire Coders -->
  <section id="why-coders">
    <h2>12. 💼 Why Companies Hire Coders for SEO</h2>

    <h3>The Problem</h3>
    <p>Marketers know <strong>what</strong> to do, but <strong>cannot edit code</strong>.</p>

    <h3>What Only Coders Can Do</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Task</th>
          <th>Marketer</th>
          <th>Coder (You)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Write content</td>
          <td>✅</td>
          <td>✅</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Edit <code>&lt;title&gt;</code></td>
          <td>❌</td>
          <td>✅</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Add Schema JSON</td>
          <td>❌</td>
          <td>✅</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Fix broken links</td>
          <td>❌</td>
          <td>✅</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Optimize images</td>
          <td>❌</td>
          <td>✅</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Debug <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> section</td>
          <td>❌</td>
          <td>✅</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <h4>🔧 Your Value</h4>
      <p>You are the <strong>builder</strong>. They are the <strong>decorators</strong>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Off-Page SEO -->
  <section id="off-page-seo">
    <h2>13. 🌐 Beyond Your Page: Off-Page SEO</h2>

    <h3>🧠 What Is Off-Page SEO?</h3>
    <p>So far, we've focused on what happens <strong>on your website</strong>—your HTML tags, your content, your structure. But SEO isn't just about what's on your page.</p>

    <p><strong>Off-Page SEO</strong> is about what happens <strong>across the rest of the internet</strong>. When other websites link to your content, mention your brand, or share your work, they're sending signals to Google about your <strong>trustworthiness</strong> and <strong>authority</strong>.</p>

    <p>Think of it like a reputation. If one person recommends a restaurant, you might try it. If <strong>hundreds</strong> of people—including food critics and news sites—all recommend the same restaurant, you'll trust it much more.</p>

    <h3>The Power of Backlinks</h3>
    <p>A <strong>backlink</strong> is simply a link from another website to yours. Each backlink is like a "vote of confidence" in your content. But not all votes are equal:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>🏛️ A link from a reputable news site = <strong>High value</strong></li>
      <li>🎓 A link from a university = <strong>High value</strong></li>
      <li>🏢 A link from an industry blog = <strong>Medium value</strong></li>
      <li>🤖 A link from a spammy site = <strong>Low or negative value</strong></li>
    </ul>

    <div class="reflect-box">
      <h4>🤔 Reflection</h4>
      <p>Why might Google trust a page that's linked from a reputable news site more than a page with no external links? Think about how you evaluate information in real life.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>What's Coming Next</h3>
    <p>In <strong>Level 4</strong>, we'll dive deep into:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>How to build quality backlinks ethically</li>
      <li>Guest posting and content partnerships</li>
      <li>Social signals and brand mentions</li>
      <li>Domain authority and trust metrics</li>
      <li>Avoiding link schemes and penalties</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="key-takeaway-box">
      <h4>🎯 Key Takeaway</h4>
      <p>Your on-page SEO gets you in the game, but off-page SEO determines if you win. Build great content, and the links will follow naturally.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="success-box">
      <h4>✅ For Now</h4>
      <p>Focus on creating valuable content that people <strong>want</strong> to link to. The rest will come with time and the strategies you'll learn in advanced levels.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Quiz Section -->
  <section id="quiz" class="quiz-section">
    <h2>🎯 Level 1 Quiz: SEO Basics</h2>
    <p>Test your understanding of SEO & GEO basics!</p>

    <form id="quiz" class="quiz-form">
      <div class="question" data-question="1">
        <p><strong>1. What does SEO stand for?</strong></p>
        <label data-letter="A"><input type="radio" name="q1" value="a"> Site Entry Optimization</label>
        <label data-letter="B"><input type="radio" name="q1" value="b"> Search Engine Optimization</label>
        <label data-letter="C"><input type="radio" name="q1" value="c"> Site Enhancement Order</label>
      </div>

      <div class="question" data-question="2">
        <p><strong>2. What is the purpose of the &lt;title&gt; tag?</strong></p>
        <label data-letter="A"><input type="radio" name="q2" value="a"> To make the page look pretty</label>
        <label data-letter="B"><input type="radio" name="q2" value="b"> To tell Google the page name</label>
        <label data-letter="C"><input type="radio" name="q2" value="c"> To create a heading</label>
      </div>

      <div class="question" data-question="3">
        <p><strong>3. How many &lt;h1&gt; tags should you have per page?</strong></p>
        <label data-letter="A"><input type="radio" name="q3" value="a"> As many as you want</label>
        <label data-letter="B"><input type="radio" name="q3" value="b"> Exactly one</label>
